== THE FULL PICTURE

_Hospital childbirth classes tend to focus on what to expect at that specific facility and how to work within their protocols. Independent classes often cover a wider range of options and decision-making frameworks._ Most hospital-based childbirth education covers facility policies, when to call, what interventions you might encounter, and how epidurals work. They present continuous monitoring, IV placement, and lying in bed as standard—because at that hospital, they are.

_Natural birth requires specialized preparation._ If you want an unmedicated birth, a hospital class won't prepare you. These programs briefly mention "breathing techniques" and "relaxation," but spend far more time on epidural procedures and cesarean recovery. You need a method specifically designed for unmedicated labor.

_The instructor's philosophy shapes what you learn._ An instructor who believes "epidurals are a blessing" will teach differently than one who's attended 100 unmedicated home births. Ask about the instructor's background, birth philosophy, and their own unmedicated birth rate if applicable.

_Partner preparation is often superficial._ Most classes tell partners to "be supportive" and "bring snacks." Methods like Bradley train partners as active labor coaches with specific techniques: hip squeezes, counter-pressure, position changes, emotional signposts. There's a massive difference.

_Starting too late means skipping practice._ If you take a one-day crash course at 38 weeks, you won't have time to internalize techniques. Hypnobirthing requires daily listening to tracks for weeks. Bradley includes nutrition and exercise protocols throughout the third trimester. These methods need time.

_Not all online classes are equal._ High-quality online courses from certified instructors can be excellent—convenient, rewatchable, and comprehensive. But many cheap programs are just someone's birth story plus generic advice. Look for credentials: RN, CNM, CCE, or method-specific certification.

