== THE BRADLEY METHOD: HUSBAND-COACHED CHILDBIRTH

=== Philosophy

The Bradley Method views birth as a natural, normal process that the body is designed to accomplish. The approach emphasizes that with proper preparation—nutrition, exercise, education, and partner support—most women can achieve unmedicated vaginal delivery.

Key principles:
- Birth is natural, not medical
- Proper nutrition is foundational (80-100g protein daily, no junk food)
- The partner is the primary labor coach
- Relaxation is a learned skill requiring practice
- Knowledge removes fear

=== Course Structure

_12-week comprehensive series_, meeting weekly for 2-3 hours. This is the longest, most in-depth program available.

Weekly topics include:
- Nutrition and pregnancy diet
- Exercise for pregnancy and labor
- Anatomy and physiology of birth
- Stages of labor in detail
- Relaxation techniques (progressive muscle relaxation)
- Breathing patterns for each stage
- Coaching techniques for partners
- Common complications and when intervention is necessary
- Breastfeeding basics
- Postpartum preparation

_Daily homework:_ Practicing relaxation (20-30 minutes), following nutrition plan, exercise routine, reading assignments.

=== Partner Role

Bradley is unique in making the partner the primary labor coach. Partners learn:
- How to assess relaxation in each muscle group
- Specific touch and massage techniques
- Counter-pressure for back labor
- Emotional signposts (recognizing transition, when she needs different support)
- Advocacy skills (speaking for her when she can't)

=== Techniques

_Relaxation:_ The core skill. You learn to consciously relax every muscle group while experiencing discomfort. This is practiced nightly during pregnancy so it becomes automatic during labor.

_Abdominal breathing:_ Slow, deep belly breathing that promotes relaxation and adequate oxygen for baby.

_Natural positions:_ Side-lying, hands-and-knees, supported squatting, standing with support—positions that work with gravity and open the pelvis.

_Tuning in:_ Internal focus. During contractions, you close your eyes, turn inward, and relax rather than talking or engaging with the room.

=== Success Rates

The American Academy of Husband-Coached Childbirth (AAHCC) reports that over 86% of Bradley Method students achieve unmedicated vaginal birth #citation[18]. However, this statistic comes from self-reported data collected by instructors, not independent research. For context, only 17% of women in the general U.S. population achieve unmedicated birth according to the Listening to Mothers III survey #citation[2].

=== Key Resources

- _Book:_ _Natural Childbirth the Bradley Way_ by Susan McCutcheon
- _Founder's book:_ _Husband-Coached Childbirth_ by Dr. Robert Bradley
- _Website:_ bradleybirth.com to find certified instructors

=== Best For

- Couples committed to unmedicated birth
- Partners who want an active, trained role
- Women who value nutrition and fitness preparation
- Those who appreciate structured, comprehensive programs
- People planning birth in any setting (hospital, birth center, home)

